What Is Constellation (DAG)?
Constellation (DAG) is a protocol that uses a directed acyclic graph architecture to achieve a consensus that is, in theory, is capable of infinite scalability. With the DAG protocol and custom state channels, Constellation is driving the evolution of smart contracts by allowing data sources to be integrated into distributed ledger technology (DLT).

The company was launched in 2017 and the DAG roadmap dates back to April 2018. When developing the project, the founding team decided to rethink the usual solutions to many of the problems for existing blockchains, such as scalability and centralization. Constellation is designed to enable the secure processing of big data, offering the ability to connect to external datasets through easy-to-use APIs. Its technology is facilitated by a change in the principle of building consensus via a serverless architecture.

Nothing. Funds are copied to the hard fork.

Transferred to the coldkey. Not lost.

messages.content: can machine learning models make mistakes?
haha yes
all the time... ChatGPT's responses contain a certain portion of BS (in terms of truth or accuracy) -- often very eloquently stated.
in fact machine learning is in many ways starting with 100% mistakes and reducing from there by training.
ish.
basically, most llm's are good at constructing sentences based on prompts, rather than answering questions correctly
google has a similar thing with its summaries if it "misunderstands" a webpage

exactly, at least in their correct form these models 'comprehend' and generate text, but were not intended to be and certainly aren't good reference sources. not by a long shot. 

nonetheless quite a few have discovered ChatGPT to be the first real contender to Google search (makes sense, it's much more direct) and in time people might trust what it says more than they should.

when you ask something, it's only when you know the topic really well that you can pick out the BS from the goods is the response -- but people often ask things they don't know very well.
interesting so making a machine learn a dataset isnt enough
for it to be 100% accurate does it have to learn the data set several times?

but again let's say if it gives BS 5% of the time, that number was likely much higher in prior iterations -- lots of real world AI applications are endeavors where you try to get the mistakes to a reasonably low rate so it can actually be useful.
or would you have to put it through several tests

it can certainly know facts from training... it will know there is 100 centimeters in a meter.... the inaccuracy would be on things that are a bit more abstracted than facts and figures... things that we might infer from other information.

these are some of the complaints but overall it's much better than GPT3 --- if you asked GPT3 a question with a false assumption (why do mice play the piano?)  it would more often than not ramble on with fictitious reasons whereas ChatGPT is more likely to say mice don't play the piano.
it cost an arm and a leg to make (billions) -- people grossly underestimate how expensive the production of intelligence is.
